No I ain’t got a gun, no I've never really been in a club, still live with parents but I’m still a thug! I’m so gangster, you can find me baking cookies at night, you out clubbin’? Well, I just made caramel delight. T-Swift and T-Pain rapping on the same track, it’s a thug story, tell me, can you handle that? I had a dream last night: I had high top Nikes, I had diamond in my mouth and diamonds on my mic, by the time I woke I was singing: I’m on a boat woah, oh. Cause I’m a singer turned rapper Shorty I’m a make ya! Straight to the top, yo Shorty I’m a take ya! You can call me T-Sweezy, now I’m a rap star Hey, it’s a thug story, now tell ’em who you are. summary: Nothing super exciting really but this could be the house taylor is reportedly looking at buying. although very very unconfirmed...
caption:
Nothing super exciting really but this could be the house taylor is reportedly looking at buying. although very very unconfirmed i thought i would do a post on it anyways. 

So according to the only property records i can find (last updated 2015) the house is owned by Gerald Davidson and his wife Simone. they have 2 sons, Joseph jack Davidson and Isaac Davidson. Joseph has also listed the property as the main correspondence address on some of his charitable foundations. Gerald’s parents Manny and Brigitta have made some headlines fighting with their children, Gerald and his sister Maxine, over property, high value jewellery etc you can find more information below if your interested. haha thanks daily mail for the gossip.

https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5978319/How-parents-victims-ao-coup-Father-lost-600m-mansion-giving-keys-children.html

https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3207501/Barred-stately-home-children-gave-fortune-600m-trust-fund-kids-French-villa-sale.html

https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4397658/Parents-locked-17m-legal-dispute-children.html

https://notaryni.com/a-warning-on-iht/

Gardnor House, Gardnor Road, London NW3 1HA

https://www.housebeautiful.com/uk/lifestyle/property/a25976850/family-home-for-sale-hampstead-london/

https://www.knightfrank.com/properties/residential/for-sale/gardnor-road-london-nw3/ham170196

This is Gardnor House. 

A stunning family home within walking distance of all village amenities and Hampstead Heath. This 5 bedroom house retains a wealth of period features and is a perfect family home enjoying landscaped rear gardens and off road parking.

Dating back to 1736, a Grade II* listed Georgian detached home located within the middle of the village.

The house extends to approx. 4,600 sqft and offers versatile and spacious accommodation across all levels.

The reception hall provides access to the secondary study that in turn leads to the kitchen/ breakfast room that opens onto the meticulously landscaped front gardens. From the reception hall, the spacious hallway leads to the downstairs w.c., cloakroom, Study that opens onto the courtyard garden and family room that opens onto the rear garden.

On the raised ground floor, the exquisite drawing room with bay window overlooking the rear garden is a particular feature, there is a separate dining room and additional guest w.c.

To the first floor there is a luxurious master suite with dressing area and beautifully fitted bathroom and a second double bedroom with shower room. 

On the second floor there is an additional bedroom with en suite bathroom, two further bedrooms and family bathroom. The laundry room is also positioned on the top floor.

The mature landscaped front and rear gardens are a particular feature of this stunning home. There is off road parking for two vehicles and a detached garage (which you can see in the pictures with the cute little smart car in the middle).   - credit right move for the info.

_____________________________________________________________

Gardnor House was built in 1736 for Thomas Gardnor. He and his wife and family owned property and developed many properties and streets in and around Hampstead and it was also once home to two very different people – at different times I might add.  One was the writer Sir Kingsley Amis (1922 – 1995).  He wrote some 20 novels plus poetry, radio and television scripts and literary criticism. Although best remembered for novels such as Lucky Jim, he originally wished to be a poet, and turned to writing novels only after publishing several volumes of verse.  He was well known to like a drink. For many years he is said to have rigorously separated his writing and his drinking.

The other was comedy actor, Betty Marsden (1919 – 1998), best known for playing multiple parts in the 1960s BBC radio series “Beyond our Ken” and “Round the Horne”. She did pop up in other things and was in a couple of Carry On films. Apparently throughout the filming of Carry on Camping in 1969, she suggested to fellow actress Dilys Laye that she wanted to die with a glass of gin in her hand. In July 1998, soon after moving into a residential home for old actors, she collapsed and died in the home’s bar. 

 An architect also once lived in the house although no further information was given about that time.

credit for most of the above paragraph: https://londonpostcodewalks.wordpress.com/2014/07/14/nw3-come-and-make-eyes-at-me/ (stop 7)

summary:
"If we loved again I swear I'd love you right"
Back to December has always held a special place in my heart. The heartfelt...
body:
“If we loved again I swear I’d love you right”

Back to December has always held a special place in my heart. The heartfelt lyrics always got in on me. But it wasn’t until a few years ago when I pushed away my very own man with tan skin and the sweetest smile did I fully understand the emotion this song carries.

(I pushed him away not because I didn’t have feelings for him too, but because I was suffering terribly with an illness and didn’t want to explain the bad side of me to someone who always lit up the room).

He has moved on and is in a relationship and quite selfishly I sometimes wonder if I could go back and not drive him away, where would we be now.
